Review Notes
Known risks
HA capability data is best effort, not guaranteed complete. Some integrations will return partial or inconsistent device capability information, so the wizard must degrade gracefully instead of assuming every device exposes a full schema.

Yes/No should remain limited to actual HA boolean helpers. Device states must use the native values HA reports, such as on/off, open/closed, detected/clear, or active/inactive.

Direct runtime file reads from globals.json should not be assumed safe until validated in the sandbox. The design needs a fallback plan if plain file I/O blocks or fails in the PyScript runtime.

Run-status reporting through HA events should be treated as best effort, not guaranteed delivery. The UI must tolerate missing or stale status.

Dry run behavior must be separated by compile target. YAML can support preview-style dry run, but PyScript cannot reliably intercept all service calls the same way.

“Call another piston” has mode-specific limits. PyScript to PyScript can be supported cleanly, YAML to YAML should be fire-and-forget only, and any wait-for-completion behavior should force conversion to Complex mode.

If globals.json is missing at runtime, the piston should log a plain-English error and stop gracefully. It should not silently fall back to hidden defaults.

Full Mode and PyScript Only should be explicit setup choices, not one blended flow. Full Mode carries YAML config implications and conflict risk with existing HA automation organization.

Companion setup should show a plain-English confirmation screen listing every change before writing anything. If the user cancels, nothing should be written. If setup fails partway through, the UI should report exactly what failed and what was created.

The YAML include requirement should be stated explicitly as automation: !include_dir_merge_list automations/. This is a one-time configuration change to let HA load YAML automations from subfolders.

PyScript deployment needs allow_code_remote: true in configuration.yaml so reload works properly.

Capability fallback behavior is needed for integrations that return incomplete data, including Zigbee, Z-Wave, MQTT, media players, and custom integrations. The wizard should show partial data and offer an Other / Manual fallback.

The UI still needs explicit rules for navigation state, unsaved changes, browser refresh behavior, back-button behavior, and WebSocket reconnect behavior.

The editor data model for nested blocks is still undefined. The design needs a concrete internal JSON structure for if/else branches, repeat bodies, and deep nesting.

The save pipeline is still undefined. The design should specify what gets written, whether save can fail, what the user sees during save, and what happens if a partial failure occurs.

The wizard decision tree is still undefined. The design needs a map of valid operators, valid comparison value types, and service parameters by capability.

The companion contract is still incomplete. It needs exact rules for capability fetching, event listening, status relay, reload calls, file access, and validation handling.

The compiler template system is still under-specified. The design needs the template format, file location, placeholder model, and the meaning of user replaceable.

Blockers
The editor cannot be implemented until the nested statement tree structure is defined.

The compiler cannot be implemented until the template system is defined.

The wizard cannot be implemented until the capability decision tree is defined.

The save flow cannot be implemented until the save pipeline is defined.

The companion cannot be implemented until its integration contract is defined.

Suggested design action
Keep the architecture decisions that are already settled, but mark the items above as required follow-up design work before coding begins.
New design clarification — manual context lookup when HA data is unclear
If PistonCore fetches device capability data from Home Assistant and the returned context is missing, incomplete, ambiguous, or clearly inconsistent with normal expectations, the wizard must not guess. Instead, PistonCore prompts the user to review the device behavior and define the missing context manually.

This applies not only when HA returns no usable capability data, but also when:

the capability name is unusual or non-standard,

the reported unit of measurement is unexpected,

the value scale appears inconsistent with normal devices of that type,

or HA exposes raw data without enough meaning for the wizard to safely determine valid operators, comparisons, or action options.

Required behavior
PistonCore always tries live HA capability data first.

If the data is clear enough, the wizard uses it directly.

If the data is unclear, partial, or missing context, the user is prompted to look it up and define it manually.

The user-defined context is stored locally and reused for that device on future runs.

The wizard must prefer showing fewer options over showing incorrect options.

No automatic translation layer should invent meaning that HA did not provide and the user did not confirm.

Example
A user installs a new luminance sensor that reports lux using an unusual attribute name, or reports values at a scale far outside what is normally expected for that device class. If PistonCore cannot confidently determine how that capability should be presented, it prompts the user to define:

what the capability represents,

what unit it uses,

whether scaling or interpretation is needed for display,

and which comparisons should be available in the wizard.

Why it matters
This keeps the system honest. PistonCore is allowed to be incomplete but correct, instead of pretending it understands every odd device report and then building bad automations from wrong assumptions.


